context: In the Middle Ages, the site of the future palace formed part of the <a4_0><a7_0>Manor of Ebury<a7_0/><a4_0/> (also called Eia). The marshy ground was watered by the <a0_0><b8_0>river Tyburn<b8_0/><a0_0/>, which still flows below the courtyard and south wing of the palace. Where the river was fordable (at Cow Ford), the village of <a5_0><b12_0>Eye Cross<b12_0/><a5_0/> grew. Ownership of the site changed hands many times; owners included Edward the Confessor and his queen consort <a1_0><b9_0>Edith of Wessex<b9_0/><a1_0/> in late Saxon times, and, after the Norman Conquest, William the Conqueror. William gave the site to <a2_0><a6_0><b10_0>Geoffrey de Mandeville<b10_0/><a6_0/><a2_0/>, who bequeathed it to the monks of <a3_0><b11_0>Westminster Abbey<b11_0/><a3_0/>.
